The '''Vanguard Unionist Progressive Party''' (VUPP), informally known as '''Ulster Vanguard''', was a [[Unionism in Ireland|unionist]] political party which existed in [[Northern Ireland]] between 1973 and 1978. It was closely affiliated with several [[Ulster loyalism|loyalist]] [[paramilitary]] groups.

==Origins==
It had its roots in the '''Vanguard''' or '''Ulster Vanguard''' wing of the [[Ulster Unionist Party]] (UUP) who were opposed to the policies of the party's leader and last [[Prime Minister of Northern Ireland]], [[Brian Faulkner]]. The Ulster Vanguard movement was originally a political pressure group within the UUP. It was formed on  9 February 1972<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/organ/uorgan.htm#uv Abstracts of Organisations - 'U'] Conflict Archive on the INternet</ref> and was led by [[William Craig (politician)|William Craig]] (former Minister of Home Affairs at [[Parliament of Northern Ireland|Stormont]]) with its deputy leaders [[Martin Smyth|Rev Martin Smyth]] and the former Stormont MP for Carrick, [[Austin Ardill|Captain Austin Ardill]].<ref>[http://www.election.demon.co.uk/stormont/biographies.html Northern Ireland Parliamentary Elections Results: Biographies] Election Demon</ref> At its first meeting in [[Lisburn]], on 13 February 1972, Craig made the first of a number of bellicose pronouncements, declaring "God help those who get in our way for we mean business."<ref>[http://www.galeuk.com/stormont/pdf/End%20of%20Stormont%20&%20imposition%20of%20direct%20rule%201972.pdf Craig's speech at Lisburn rally] Cengage Learning</ref>

After the suspension of the [[Parliament of Northern Ireland|Stormont Parliament]], Faulkner moved towards a policy of power-sharing with nationalist and non-sectarian politicians under the [[Sunningdale Agreement]]. In opposition to this many in the Ulster Unionists broke away and founded a separate Vanguard Party, with William Craig as the leader.

==Ideology==
Vanguard is usually considered to have been a right-wing party. In its earliest days it adopted the style associated with [[falangist]] parties with an honour guard, a common salute and a habit of wearing sashes. This led to it being characterised as [[Oswald Mosley|Mosleyite]]<ref>[http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qps14mSlghcC&pg=PA263&lpg=PA263&dq=vanguard+unionist+party&source=web&ots=2i3PM1JGR5&sig=xcyvhUds4BUmw4PO8Cm0W8P5W4I&hl=en Encyclopedia of British and Irish Political Organisations, Barberis/McHugh/Tyldesley (2003) p263] Google Books</ref> or even neo-Nazi <ref name="books.google.co.uk">[http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3q3wYR8gWusC&pg=PA89&lpg=PA89&dq=vanguard+unionist+party&source=web&ots=QmFErtot7o&sig=ElvGLfIFaYFGRS2QrCqruL7xRmY&hl=en Indispensible Traitors:Liberal Parties in settler conflicts by Thomas G. Mitchell, p89] Google Books</ref> with the Stormont MP [[Robert Dodd McConnell|William McConnell]] claiming that Vanguard rallies involved "a certain Hitlerian-type figure ... walking up and down the lines, inspecting his so-called storm-troopers."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stormontpapers.ahds.ac.uk/stormontpapers/pageview.html?volumeno=84&pageno=621&searchTerm=vanguard#bak-84-623 |title=The Stormont Papers <U+2013> Volume 84, p621 |publisher=Stormontpapers.ahds.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2010-06-15}}</ref>

Ulster Vanguard was intended to provide an umbrella organisation for various loyalist groups.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/recent/troubles/the_troubles_article_05.shtml The troubles article] BBC History</ref> 
It had close links with, and strong support from Loyalist paramilitary groups. Vanguard had its own paramilitary grouping called the Vanguard Service Corps (USC) whose main function seemed to be to provide escorts for Vanguard speakers attending rallies.<ref>[http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=fnSfu-ivcSwC&pg=RA6-PA106&lpg=RA6-PA106&dq=vanguard+service+corps&source=web&ots=F_cgdI4eQU&sig=2L1MoTQAZxvc3JFx-781rCFmU9A&hl=en Political parties and terrorist groups by Leonard Weinberg, p106] Google Books</ref>

==Policies==
Vanguard strongly criticised the imposition of direct rule and in its booklet 'Ulster &ndash; A Nation' published in April 1972, it pledged "resistance to an undemocratic and un-British regime" and suggested the possibility of a Federal British Isles.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/organ/docs/vanguard72.htm CAIN: Ulster Vanguard (1972) Ulster - A Nation] Conflict Archive on the INternet</ref>

At the Darlington Conference in September 1972, held to discuss various constitutional options for Northern Ireland, they proposed the restoration of the Northern Ireland Parliament as a single chamber assembly with a committee system to ensure greater participation by all parties. Internal security responsibilities would be restored however there would be a [[Bill of Rights]] to safeguard the rights of minorities.<ref name="Mulholland">{{cite web |url=http://www.galeuk.com/stormont/pdf/End%20of%20Stormont%20&%20imposition%20of%20direct%20rule%201972.pdf |format=PDF|title=The End of Stormont and imposition of direct rule in 1972 |author=Dr Marc Mulholland, St Catherine<U+2019>s College, Oxford |publisher=Cengage Learning|accessdate=15 April 2008}}</ref>

It demanded the "extermination" of the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] and a reversal of the reforms introduced by Brian Faulkner and his predecessor, and in a booklet published in late 1972 entitled 'Community of the British Isles' it even flirted with the idea of full independence for Northern Ireland albeit within a structure which would also include Great Britain and the Republic of Ireland.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/organ/docs/vanguard72a.htm CAIN: Ulster Vanguard (n.d.,1972?) Community of the British Isles] Conflict Archive on the INternet</ref> 

In late 1973 it rejected the idea of compulsory power sharing with Irish Nationalists and consequently refused invitations to take part in the conferences which led to the [[Sunningdale Agreement]].<ref>[http://www.uhb.fr/langues/cei/nicons74.htm White paper the Northern Ireland Constitution Part 2, 13] Universit<U+00E9> Rennes 2</ref>

In their 1974 Westminster manifesto, they called for the more mainstream Unionist option of either devolved government with full security responsibilities or full integration into the UK.<ref name="Mulholland" />

However there were occasions when it did not follow the same course as other right-wing or unionist parties. For example in [[United Kingdom referendum, 1975|the 1975 referendum]] on the United Kingdom's membership of the-then [[European Economic Community]], it campaigned for the United Kingdom to remain a member whilst the other Unionist parties campaigned for withdrawal.<ref>[http://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/fref70s.htm The Referendums of 1973 and 1975] ARK - Access Research Knowledge</ref>

===Extra-Parliamentary activity===
Vanguard was firmly supportive of extra-parliamentary activity in the form of direct action in order to achieve its goals. On 26 January 1972, Craig announced plans to hold large rallies in major centres in Northern Ireland<ref name="galeuk.com">[http://www.galeuk.com/stormont/pdf/End%20of%20Stormont%20&%20imposition%20of%20direct%20rule%201972.pdf The end of Stormont and the imposition of direct rule] Cengage Learning</ref> The culmination was a large rally on 18 March 1972 in Belfast's Ormeau Park, attended by up to 60,000&nbsp;people, at which Craig said that "We must build up the dossiers on the men and women who are a menace to this country, because one day, ladies and gentlement, if the politicians fail, it will be our duty to liquidate the enemy".<ref>Boyd, Andrew, 1972, Brian Faulkner and the Crisis of Ulster Unionism, Anvil Books, Tralee, Republic of Ireland. p100</ref>

Following the suspension of Stormont and the imposition of direct rule in March 1972, Vanguard organised a general strike which affected power supplies, caused businesses to close and halted public transport.<ref>[http://falcon.arts.cornell.edu/dg78/100.3/documents/ira2.htm Northern Ireland <U+2013> History and Current Status of <U+201C>The Troubles<U+201D>]{{dead link|date=June 2010}}</ref> About 190,000&nbsp;people participated and Vanguard members barricaded and took effective control of the town of [[Portadown]].<ref name="galeuk.com"/> Later 100,000&nbsp;unionists converged on the drive leading to Stormont, where Craig addressed the crowds, but deferred to the outgoing Prime Minister Brian Faulkner who managed to disperse the crowds.
On 3 June 1972, VUPP organised a march in [[Derry]] against the creation of no-go areas in [[Irish nationalism|Nationalist]] districts which ended in violence on the city's Craigavon bridge. Despite the violence, Craig pledged to continue the marches stating: "We are no longer protesting - we are demanding action."<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/june/3/newsid_2496000/2496155.stm VUPP organises march in Derry] BBC News</ref>

In February 1973 it was one of the only parties to support the two-day general strike organised by the [[Loyalist Association of Workers]] in protest at the internment of Protestants. <ref name="books.google.co.uk"/> The strike had the further stated goal to "re-establish some kind of Protestant or loyalist control over the affairs in the province, especially over security policy" The strike resulted in high levels of violence with five people, including a fireman, being killed, seven people wounded, several explosions and numerous malicious fires.
<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/events/uwc/bac.htm Background to the Ulster Workers Council Strike] Conflict Archive on the INternet</ref> 

The strike proved to be a forerunner of the [[Ulster Workers Council Strike]] the following year, in which  VUPP again played a prominent role, making their headquarters in Hawthornden Road, Belfast, available to the strike leaders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=liiq7RU67OoC&pg=PA36&lpg=PA36&dq=ernest+baird+vanguard&source=web&ots=azFsMFDtFh&sig=4LbGo7efMmRpA6NWxzvVDu9yvqc&hl=en |title=Crimes of loyalty: A history of the UDA by Ian Wood, p36-7 |publisher=Books.google.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2010-06-15}}</ref> with Craig a leading member of the UWC coordinating committee<ref>[http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qps14mSlghcC&pg=PA260&lpg=PA260&dq=william+craig+uwc+strike&source=web&ots=2i3PM6JAZ4&sig=RTN9yWSNwEVH40ZdG4aJJmiEZ3k&hl=en#PPA260,M1 Encyclopedia of British and Irish political organizations] Google Books</ref>

In addition to large rallies, Vanguard used other tactics in order to try to put pressure on the British Government. In July 1972, they called for a rent and rate strike, a proposal which put them at odds with other unionist parties and which was criticized by the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]].<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1972/jul/24/northern-ireland#S5CV0841P0-04744 NORTHERN IRELAND] Hansard, 24 July 1972, Col.1350</ref> Several months later, on 19 October 1972, Craig addressed a meeting of the right wing [[Conservative Monday Club]] during which he claimed he could mobilise 80,000&nbsp;men <U+201C>who are prepared to come out and shoot and kill.<U+201D><ref>[http://www.taoiseach.gov.ie/attached_files/Pdf%20files/Dublin_Barron_Rep031204.pdf Interim Report on the Report of the Commission of Enquiry into the 1972 Dublin bombings, p12] Office of the Taoiseach</ref>

==Electoral performances==
The party contested a succession of elections: to the brief Sunningdale Assembly, the [[United Kingdom general election, February 1974|February 1974 General Election]], the [[United Kingdom general election, October 1974|October 1974 General Election]] and the 1975 elections to the Constitutional Convention. The 1973 Sunningdale and local council elections were fought in an informal alliance with the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]] as "the loyalist coalition" while the latter three were fought as part of the [[United Ulster Unionist Council]], a more formal arrangement, with the [[Democratic Unionist Party]] and the Ulster Unionists, where the anti-Sunningdale wing of the party was now in control.

