'''Source''':<ref>[http://www.ark.ac.uk/elections Northern Ireland elections] ARK - Access Research Knowledge</ref>

The number of Vanguard councillors elected in 1973 is a matter of some dispute among the various sources, as Whyte<ref>[http://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/flg73.htm 1973 Local Government elections] ARK - Access Research Knowledge</ref> notes: "there is huge potential for confusion among the various candidate designations." As a minimum, James Knight, writing closest to the time, counted eight councillors<ref>James Knight and Nicolas Baxter-Moore's Northern Ireland Local Government Elections, 1973</ref> CAIN counts nine Vanguard councillors - counting an additional councillor in [[Ards Borough Council|Ards]]. Whyte counts ten, ignoring the councillor in Ards but counting two additional councillors in [[Craigavon Borough Council|Craigavon]] who he says were described as Vanguard councillors on the ballot paper.<ref>[http://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/73-81lgcraigavon.htm Craigavon 1973 local election results] ARK - Access Research Knowledge</ref>

However in addition to the eleven above, a further thirteen councillors elected in 1973 (usually under a 'loyalist' label) contested the 1977 local elections either for Vanguard or for their splinter party, the [[United Ulster Unionist Party]]. This includes seven councillors elected as loyalists in 1973 who ran as VUPP candidates in 1977, namely Seymour, Armstrong, Semple and Stewart ([[Larne Borough Council|Larne]]), Green and Mary O'Fee ([[North Down Borough Council|North Down]]) and [[Glenn Barr]] ([[Derry City Council|Londonderry]].) A further four sitting councillors elected as Loyalists stood as UUUP candidates in 1977, namely McKeever (Larne), Ritchie ([[Carrickfergus Borough Council|Carrickfergus]]), Scott ([[Castlereagh Borough Council|Castlereagh]]) and Parke ([[Cookstown District Council|Cookstown]]). Ben Horan, elected as a 'Unionist' in [[Belfast City Council|Belfast]] in 1973, announced two days after the election in the local press that he would sit as a VUPP councillor<ref>Belfast Telegraph, 1 June 1973, p10</ref> although he stood in 1977 as a UUUP candidate. Finally, Randall Crawford, elected in [[Coleraine Borough Council|Coleraine]] in 1973 and 1977 as a non-party candidate, stood for [[Londonderry (Assembly constituency)|Londonderry]] in the 1975 Constitutional convention election as a VUPP candidate.<ref>[http://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/cldy.htm 1975 Londonderry Convention election result] ARK - Access Research Knowledge</ref> 

A further councillor, Mrs M. Corrie, elected in Castlereagh as a United Loyalist, is described in contemporary press reports as a Vanguard councillor, but did not contest the 1977 local elections.<ref>[http://www.marxists.org/history/etol/newspape/isj/1974/no070/miller.htm International Socialism No.70 p17-21] Marxists Internet Archive</ref>
   
During the 1973-75 period VUPP was able to match or even beat the DUP in several elections. However their prospects of replacing the DUP as the second party of Unionism came to grief as a result of events during the Constitutional Convention.

==1975/76 Split==
The Constitutional Convention was intended to serve as a forum to allow the politicians of Northern Ireland to draw up their own proposals for the political future of the province, though this proved unsuccessful. However it led to William Craig proposing a voluntary coalition with the Nationalist [[Social Democratic and Labour Party|SDLP]] in the event of there being a state of emergency. The move was a considerable surprise with a confidential government memo commenting: <U+201C>Mr. Craig appears to some as a knight in shining armour. The fact is that his aims were &ndash; and still are &ndash; simple: to get a devolved government which would control security policy as quickly as possible, on the basis of a gentleman's agreement that the SDLP would participate in government for a year or two.<U+201D> <ref name="nationalarchives.gov.uk">[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/releases/2005/highlights_december/december29/northernireland.htm National Archives 19 September 1975, Catalogue ref CAB 134/3921] National Archives</ref> But any idea of power sharing was anathema to many Unionist in the post-Sunningdale climate of 1975. Indeed in January 1976, Deputy leader Ernest Baird warned that <U+201C>If Westminster does not accept the Protestants' rejection of power-sharing, it must face the inevitable consequences of a final conflict."<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,913890-2,00.html Down the Road to Hell] Time Magazine, 19 January 1976</ref>

As a result the party was bitterly split with only [[David Trimble]] and [[Glenn Barr]] backing Craig with the other eleven convention members challenging Craig's leadership. Craig however claimed that he had the backing of the party's rank and file and this was confirmed when sixty percent of party members and backed him at a specially convened meeting. The dissidents then broke away to form what would later become the [[United Ulster Unionist Party]].

On 8 September 1975, Craig<U+2019>s proposals were decisively rejected at a meeting of the UUUC with 37&nbsp;votes against and only Craig voting in favour.<ref name="nationalarchives.gov.uk"/> Consequently, Craig and the rump of VUPP were expelled from the UUUC.<ref>[http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qps14mSlghcC&pg=PA262&lpg=PA262&dq=vanguard+unionist+uuup&source=web&ots=2i3PM7AzW9&sig=76vOV-dseYVWzf67BNSUZAFZpW0&hl=en Encyclopedia of British and Irish Political Organisations, p899] Google Books</ref>

==Decline and disbandment==
The 1977 local elections were overshadowed by the abortive United Unionist Action Council (UUAC) Strike which was mainly supported by the DUP and the UUUM. In contrast to 1974, when they had played a prominent role in the previous strike Vanguard criticized the strike and together with the UUP and Orange Order, called for it to be abandoned.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/events/uuac/chron.htm Chronology of UUAC 1977 strike] Conflict Archive on the INternet</ref>

The 1977 council elections were seen as a crucial test of Vanguard's ability to survive as a party and ultimately the party failed that test. Although thirteen councilors elected in 1973 stood as VUPP candidates, the party emerged from the election with only five councillors<ref>[http://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/flg77.htm 1977 council election results] ARK - Access Research Knowledge</ref> compared to twelve councilors elected in 1977 for their breakaway rival the UUUP.

Craig then applied to rejoin the UUP in February 1978 and subsequently merged the remainder of Vanguard back into the Ulster Unionist Party, where it returned to its origin as a pressure group within the UUP as the Vanguard movement, although this too seems to have quickly faded away. The [[Democratic Unionist Party]] subsequently became the main Unionist party offering a more right wing alternative position to the Ulster Unionists.
In the 1982 elections for the new Northern Ireland Assembly, Craig, who had once more left the Ulster Unionists after losing his seat at Westminster, revived the name Vanguard for his candidacy in [[Belfast East (Assembly constituency)|East Belfast]]. However he failed to get elected.

==Prominent UUP members in Vanguard==
Several prominent current Ulster Unionist politicians were members of Vanguard, including future UUP MP [[David Burnside]] (who was Vanguard's press officer from 1974 to 1977<ref>[http://www.uup.org/people_davidburnside.htm Burnside profile] Ulster Unionist Party</ref>) while those elected for VUPP in 1975 included future UUP leaders [[David Trimble]] (who briefly served as Vanguard Deputy Leader) and [[Reg Empey]] who served as Vanguard chairman from 1974-75.<ref>[http://www.niassembly.gov.uk/members/biogs_03/empey_r.htm Biography of Reg Empey] Northern Ireland Assembly</ref> Former deputy speaker of the Northern Ireland Assembly, [[Jim Wilson (UK politician)|Jim Wilson]], served as a Vanguard councillor on [[Newtownabbey Borough Council]] from 1975 to 1976 before joining the UUP<ref>[http://www.niassembly.gov.uk/Speakers_Office/DSbiography.htm Jim Wilson biography] NI Assembly</ref> [[Martin Smyth|rev. Martin Smyth]] later a UUP MP and Grand Master of the [[Orange Institution|Orange Order]] was deputy leader of the Vanguard movement but declined to join the party.

